<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="roadmap-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-planning</domain>
    <summary>Strategic communication tool showing where the product is going and why. Choose format by uncertainty level: Now-Next-Later for medium, timeline for committed work, outcome-themed for high.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>roadmap</tag>
      <tag>strategy</tag>
      <tag>planning</tag>
      <tag>now-next-later</tag>
      <tag>objectives</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Roadmap Design</title>
    <summary>A roadmap is a strategic communication tool showing where the product is going and why — not a feature list with dates. Choose the format by uncertainty level: Now-Next-Later for medium uncertainty (default), timeline for committed work, outcome-themed for high uncertainty. Every initiative must link to a stated objective; every theme must have a measurable success metric.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Timeline roadmaps with hard dates always slip and erode trust. Now-Next-Later rarely does, because it communicates priority sequence without false precision. Linking every initiative to an objective prevents roadmaps from becoming wish lists and gives stakeholders a reason to agree with the ordering.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quarterly planning where strategy must be communicated to team, stakeholders, or customers.</item>
        <item>After RICE/MoSCoW prioritization — the roadmap is the consumable form of those rankings.</item>
        <item>Multiple audiences (engineering, sales, customers) need different slices of the same plan.</item>
        <item>Strategic alignment check: does planned work actually drive stated objectives?</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Less than 4 weeks of work ahead — a sprint plan or kanban suffices.</item>
        <item>Pre-PMF discovery phase — use opportunity solution trees and continuous-discovery instead.</item>
        <item>High-uncertainty research with no shippable outcome — write a research charter instead.</item>
        <item>One-person, one-week feature — overhead is not justified.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="framework">
      <p>Four roadmap types exist, each matching a different uncertainty and stakeholder context: timeline format for low-uncertainty, committed work (typical in regulated enterprise). Now-Next-Later for medium uncertainty (default for most solopreneurs and early-stage products). Outcome-themed roadmaps for high uncertainty research and discovery phases. Kanban boards for live execution and reactive reprioritization. Selecting the wrong format leads to either false precision (timeline when uncertain) or insufficient guidance (outcome-themed when execution clarity is needed). A format selection matrix based on uncertainty and audience guides the choice.</p>
      <p>A 5-step design process converts strategy inputs into consumable roadmap artifacts and prepares stakeholder communication. Strategy inputs are collected before defining themes. Themes are defined with objective linkage and measurable success metrics. Initiatives within themes are tagged with confidence levels tied to past delivery calibration. Explicit exclusions prevent scope creep. Regular review cadence (monthly check-in, quarterly rewrite) maintains trust and reality synchronization.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Select roadmap format by uncertainty level: low uncertainty → timeline; medium → Now-Next-Later; high → outcome-themed; live execution → kanban.</statement>
        <rationale>Timeline format with hard dates always slips and erodes trust when uncertainty is high. Now-Next-Later communicates priority without false precision and is the default for early-stage products.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Now-Next-Later as the default internal format unless you have high confidence in delivery dates AND a stakeholder audience that requires commitments.</statement>
        <rationale>PMs who default to timeline roadmaps spend more time explaining slippage than building. Now-Next-Later shifts the conversation to priority, not dates.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Generate two artifacts from one source — internal (with confidence levels, dependencies) and external (with capability descriptions, no internals). Never maintain them in parallel.</statement>
        <rationale>Parallel maintenance diverges within one cycle. One source of truth with a formatter subagent prevents inconsistency and saves the PM from double-editing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>5-Step Design Process:</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 1 — Collect strategy inputs before defining themes: product vision, business goals for the period, user research insights, and technical constraints.</statement>
        <rationale>Themes without strategic inputs produce feature-grouped buckets, not outcome-driven work areas.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 2 — Define 3–5 themes per period; each theme must name the objective it drives and provide 2–3 example initiatives.</statement>
        <rationale>More than 5 themes is aspirational for solo/small teams and dilutes focus. Each theme without an objective link cannot be defended under prioritization pressure.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 3 — Tag each initiative with a confidence level (high/medium/low) and treat "high" as a commitment only when scoped and spec'd.</statement>
        <rationale>Stakeholders interpret "high confidence" as a promise. Calibrate against past quarter delivery to set a realistic confidence mix.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 4 — Always include a "Not Doing" section with explicit exclusions and reasons.</statement>
        <rationale>The cheapest scope-creep prevention. A roadmap without "Not Doing" is an invitation to add more.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 5 — Review monthly, rewrite quarterly. Add a "last updated" date prominently. Cap "Later" at 8 items; cull once per quarter.</statement>
        <rationale>Stale roadmaps lose trust faster than missing ones. "Later" becomes a dumping ground without a cull policy.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="examples">
      <p>Two Now-Next-Later roadmap examples — a B2B SaaS product and a solo indie product — showing how themes tie to objectives and how "Later" is capped with explicit exclusions.</p>
      <example type="good" title="B2B SaaS Roadmap">
        <note>Internal Now-Next-Later with three themes, confidence levels, and explicit "Not Doing."</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
## NOW (Q1 — Objective: Reduce time-to-value)
Theme: Onboarding
- Guided setup wizard — In Progress — High confidence
- Template library (5 defaults) — Planned — High confidence

Theme: Performance
- API response p95 < 200ms — Planned — High confidence

## NEXT (Q2 — Objective: Enterprise readiness)
Theme: Collaboration
- Team roles and permissions — Confidence: High
- Slack integration — Confidence: Medium

Theme: Compliance
- SOC 2 audit prep — Confidence: Medium
- Depends on: security review complete by end of Q1

## LATER (exploring, cap 8 items)
- Mobile app (pending user research validation)
- AI-powered insights (spike needed)

Not Doing:
- On-premise deployment — not in ICP; revisit if 3 enterprise deals blocked
- White-labeling — low demand signal this quarter
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Solo Product Roadmap">
        <note>Solo indie product, 3 themes max per period, shorter horizons.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
## NOW
Theme: Core polish (drives: MLP target)
- Payment integration — In Progress
- Error message improvements — Planned
- Basic usage analytics — Planned

## NEXT
Theme: Growth (drives: referral goal)
- Email drip sequence — Confidence: High
- Referral program — Confidence: Medium

## LATER
- Template marketplace (external contribution model — unvalidated)
- Team features (no demand signal yet)

Not Doing:
- Mobile app — responsive web covers 95% of sessions
- Zapier integration — API-first is Q3 at earliest
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <p>Six common roadmap failures that either over-commit or under-communicate, with root causes and fixes.</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Feature list with hard delivery dates shared externally.</description>
        <reason>Customers interpret dates as commitments. When dates slip — and they always do — trust erodes. Use abstracted time horizons ("H1 2026") or capability descriptions with no dates for external sharing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Every initiative tagged "high confidence."</description>
        <reason>Confidence inflation means the signal is meaningless. Calibrate against the past quarter: if you delivered 60% of "high" items, label the rest "medium." Stakeholders will notice the discrepancy if you don't.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>"Later" bucket grows without bound.</description>
        <reason>Without a cull policy "Later" becomes a graveyard that discredits the whole roadmap. Cap at 8 items and run one quarterly cull pass; items that survive 3 culls without moving to Now/Next should be dropped or converted into discovery work.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Same roadmap artifact shared with all audiences (engineering, customers, executives, sales).</description>
        <reason>Engineering needs dependencies and confidence; customers need capability descriptions; executives need objective linkage. One artifact leaks too much or too little to each. Generate two versions from one source.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Initiatives on the roadmap not linked to any stated objective.</description>
        <reason>Unanchored initiatives cannot be prioritized or defended. If an initiative does not drive a stated OKR or goal, ask why it is on the roadmap before adding it.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Roadmap never updated between quarterly rewrites.</description>
        <reason>Monthly reviews catch reality drift before it compounds. A roadmap that was accurate in January and reviewed in April has three months of silent divergence baked in — the team loses trust that the document reflects reality.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/now-next-later.md" purpose="Internal roadmap with themes, confidence levels, dependencies, and not-doing section"/>
      <template path="templates/quarterly-outcome.md" purpose="Quarterly roadmap tied to OKRs with initiative table per theme"/>
      <template path="templates/external-roadmap.md" purpose="Customer-facing roadmap with capability descriptions and disclaimer"/>
      <template path="templates/roadmap-diff.py" purpose="Script: diff two roadmap JSON snapshots and report moved/added/dropped initiatives"/>
    </templates>
